g.title: Folded Corner.69
g.desc: The Composite patterns compliments the Single Responsibility ...

g.text: The Composite patterns compliments the Single Responsibility Principle. The pattern shifts collection management from client to composite object, to gain readability and reusability across the code base. Readability, because our client code is not obscured by ‘loops’ and collections. Reusability, because multiple clients can use the same collection management (=Composite) object. The Composite object can perform collection management with Leaf objects, but also with itself. This is why the Composite should comply to the same interface as the Leafs. The interface should be uniform.

g.title: Folded Corner.97
g.desc: Clients often use collections incase they need to compose a g...

g.text: Clients often use collections incase they need to compose a group of objects. The group of objects is often used to realize a common functionality by iterating over them. This results in that the client needs to fulfill this responsibility. We could end up with duplicate code incase we have more clients that also group these objects together in collections. To shift this responsibility to a ‘centralized’ place we can situate the ‘composite’ object, often composed of a collection, behind the same interface as our individual objects. This results in that we can use individual and composite objects uniformly.

g.title: Folded Corner.116
g.desc: The Composite pattern requires child management operations (e...

g.text: The Composite pattern requires child management operations (e.g. ‘Add’ and/or ‘Remove’) for the composite. These operations could be part of the Component interface. However, this violates ISP, because Leafs will be dependent on functions they don’t use. This could result in a default implementation in the Abstract component class. E.g. an empty function. However, this could cause a potential bug, because the client needs to ‘carefully’ monitor the component it works with to not get ‘trapped’ by unexpected, hidden situations. Another default implementation could be to throw an exception, however this forces clients to be cautious about possible exceptions, resulting in exception handling. Additionally, all Leafs need to recompile incase child management operations change. A solution could be to move the child management operations to the Composite alone. However, this requires the Composite to be type casted incase we need to add or remove child elements. We end up with type checking incase we are not sure if a composite object is behind the Component interface (cyclomatic complexity).

g.title: Folded Corner.120
g.desc: The Composite pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. ...

g.text: The Composite pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. Client code does not require change in case a Composite is used instead of a Leaf. This is because the Composite complies to the same interface.
